Visualizing NBA season game results with Holoviews¶

(Image source: fivethirtyeight)

(Image source: Holoviews)

Getting the data¶

We'll grab some NBA game data from basketball-reference.com using pandas' read_html function, which returns a list of DataFrames. Pandas' read_html is pretty good. On simple websites it almost always works. It provides a couple parameters for controlling what gets selected from the webpage if the defaults fail. It is always good to use it first, before moving on to BeautifulSoup or lxml if the page is more complicated.

We will be used the data for the last three seasons including the current one, i.e. 2016-2018 seasons.

class Downloader(object):
    def __init__(self, year, months, filepath):
        self.year = year
        self.months = months
        self.filepath = pathlib.Path(filepath)
        self.games = self.download_dataset()

    def scrape(self, month):
        base_url = "https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/NBA_" + self.year + "_games"
        url = base_url + "-" + month + ".html"
        tables = pd.read_html(url)
        games = tables[0]
        return games

    def download_dataset(self):
        games = []
        if not pathlib.Path.exists(self.filepath):
            for month in self.months:
                data = self.scrape(month)
                # store DataFrame in list
                games.append(data)

            # Use pd.concat to merge a list of DataFrame into a single big DataFrame.
            games = pd.concat(games, axis=0)
            games.to_csv(self.filepath, index=False)
            return games

        else:
            games = pd.read_csv(self.filepath)
            return games

column_names = {
    'Date': 'date',
    'Start (ET)': 'start',
    '\xa0': 'box',
    'Visitor/Neutral': 'away_team',
    'PTS': 'away_points',
    'Home/Neutral': 'home_team',
    'PTS.1': 'home_points',
    '\xa0.1': 'n_ot',
    'Attend.': 'attendance'
}
In [10]:
def clean_dataframe(games):
    games = (games.rename(columns=column_names).dropna(thresh=4).drop(
        columns=['Notes', 'n_ot', 'attendance', 'box']
    ).assign(
        date=lambda x: pd.to_datetime(x['date'], infer_datetime_format=True))
             )  #format='%a, %b %d, %Y')))
    #.set_index('date', append=True).rename_axis(["game_id","date"]).sort_index())
    return games

    width=900,
    height=500,
    tools=['hover'],
    logz=True,
    invert_yaxis=True,
    xrotation=90,
    labelled=[],
    toolbar='below',
    xaxis=None)

cv_opts = dict(
    width=500, height=300, tools=['hover'], labelled=[], toolbar='above')

bars_opts = dict(tools=['hover'])

overlay_opts = dict(width=900, height=200, show_title=False)

vline_opts = dict(line_color='black')

dist_opts = dict(show_label=False)
opts = {
    'HeatMap': {
        'plot': hm_opts
    },
    'Overlay': {
        'plot': overlay_opts
    },
    'VLine': {
        'style': vline_opts
    },
    'Curve': {
        'plot': cv_opts
    },
    'Bars': {
        'plot': bars_opts
    },
    'Distribution': {
        'plot': dist_opts
    }
}

ErrorBars provide a visual indicator for the variability of the plotted data on a graph. They are usually applied on top of other plots such as scatter, curve or bar plots to indicate the variability in each sample.

Let's use ErrorBars to visualize the variability of home team points and away team points over the 2017-2018 Season.

In [27]:
#%%opts Curve [width=600]
agg = ds_2018.aggregate('date', function=np.mean, spreadfn=np.std)
err = (hv.Curve(agg).opts(opts) * hv.ErrorBars(
    agg, vdims=['home_points', 'home_points_std'
                ]).iloc[::2]).redim.range(home_points=(0, None))
Mod(title='Variability of Home Team Points vs Away Team Points',
    toolbar_location='right').apply(err)

a = (hv.Distribution(ds_2016, kdims=['away_points']) * hv.Distribution(
    ds_2016, kdims=['home_points']))
b = hv.Distribution(
    ds_2017, kdims=['away_points']) * hv.Distribution(
        ds_2017, kdims=['home_points'])
c = hv.Distribution(
    ds_2018, kdims=['away_points']) * hv.Distribution(
        ds_2018, kdims=['home_points'])
d = a + b + c
Mod(xlabel='Points', ylabel='Points Density').apply(d)
Out[29]:

Use scipy.stats.sem() to calculate the standard error of the mean (or standard error of measurement) of the values

                                                  'opponent sem')]
agg_2017 = ds_2017.aggregate('home_team', function=np.mean, spreadfn=ss.sem)
agg_2018 = ds_2018.aggregate('home_team', function=np.mean, spreadfn=ss.sem)

b = hv.Bars(agg_2018, vdims=vdims)
